      ],
      "notes": "Intervocalic and post-nasal voicing of the stop series — the central allophonic process of Tamil (Keane 2004: 111-116, Journal of the IPA 34(1); Krishnamurti 2003: 4.2; Schiffman 1999: ch. 1). A single plosive between vowels, or after a nasal, is voiced: புத்தகம் [put̪ːaɡam], எதிரி [ed̪iɾi], நன்கொடை [nanɡoɖai]. Every other medial context is ruled out before this rule is reached (TA_GEM*_ for geminates, TA_NOVOICE_* for obstruent/liquid clusters), and word_initial=false excludes the initial position, so what is left IS the intervocalic / post-nasal environment: the previous lattice slot is either a vowel, a consonant that carries its own vowel, or a vowel-less nasal. The palatal ⟨ச⟩ lenites to [s] between vowels but voices to [dʑ] after a nasal (Keane 2004: 113; Schiffman 1999), so it takes two rules rather than one."
